        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4210551316" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9728133188704514429">A dysfunctional family get together at Christmas – sounds like a pretty average story, accept the father is Henry II of England, his wife who has been released from prison for this family reunion is Elanor of Aquitaine. Bring in Henry’s mistress, Alice, who is betrothed to one of his sons, and 3 sons who are plotting to take the crown from their father, and it sounds like a farce.<br/><br/>I’m currently reading <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18623029.The_Plantagenets_The_Warrior_Kings_and_Queens_Who_Made_England' title='The Plantagenets The Warrior Kings and Queens Who Made England by Dan Jones' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Plantagenets </a> where the events in this play are more fiction than fact but it was an entert</span>
  <span id="freeText9728133188704514429" style="display:none">A dysfunctional family get together at Christmas – sounds like a pretty average story, accept the father is Henry II of England, his wife who has been released from prison for this family reunion is Elanor of Aquitaine. Bring in Henry’s mistress, Alice, who is betrothed to one of his sons, and 3 sons who are plotting to take the crown from their father, and it sounds like a farce.<br /><br />I’m currently reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18623029.The_Plantagenets_The_Warrior_Kings_and_Queens_Who_Made_England" title="The Plantagenets The Warrior Kings and Queens Who Made England by Dan Jones" rel="nofollow noopener">The Plantagenets </a> where the events in this play are more fiction than fact but it was an entertaining 100 mins with its sharp snappy dialogue and strong female characters. The only question I have is why hadn’t Shakespeare written a play about Henry II? <br /><br /><br />(side note: read dates showing when I started and finished reading this are an approximation as this was read sometime between July and August 2021)</span>
