    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3184956049" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3184956049" />
    <a title="Nicole-Rose" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52457100-nicole-rose"><img alt="Nicole-Rose" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636570268p2/52457100.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3184956049?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nicole-Rose" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nicole-Rose" href="/user/show/52457100-nicole-rose">Nicole-Rose</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780573611605" href="/book/show/279663.The_Lion_in_Winter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52457100-nicole-rose?shelf=angevin-shenans">angevin-shenans</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52457100-nicole-rose?shelf=drama">drama</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52457100-nicole-rose?shelf=plantagenet">plantagenet</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52457100-nicole-rose?shelf=richard-i">richard-i</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3184956049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4383025192883505534"><b>Remarks:</b> Have you ever had a new book sit on your shelf for weeks without being read and you can&apos;t start it because you&apos;re waiting for that <i>perfect</i> moment to start reading it? Then after you finish it you wonder how stupid you were for letting it sit there for so long? Yeah, me too.  <br/><br/>Goldman&apos;s <i>The Lion in Winter</i> was just as good as the incredible hype surrounding it. As character-driven as this play was, I feel it would only be appropriate to go over some of its stand-out characters one-by-one. </span>
  <span id="freeText4383025192883505534" style="display:none"><b>Remarks:</b> Have you ever had a new book sit on your shelf for weeks without being read and you can't start it because you're waiting for that <i>perfect</i> moment to start reading it? Then after you finish it you wonder how stupid you were for letting it sit there for so long? Yeah, me too.  <br /><br />Goldman's <i>The Lion in Winter</i> was just as good as the incredible hype surrounding it. As character-driven as this play was, I feel it would only be appropriate to go over some of its stand-out characters one-by-one. Before that, I literally only have <i>one</i> gripe. Even after reading the author's note about his anachronistic depiction of Christmas, I still found it really distracting to picture the eaglets decorating a Christmas tree and Eleanor wrapping Christmas presents for her sons. I really don't think these elements were necessary. It may have been added for comedic effect, but I feel as if the play could have been even better without them. <br /><br />So let's get on with it. <br /><br /><i>"My life, when it is written, will read better than it lived."</i> - Henry<br /><br /><b>Henry:</b> Henry definitely had the most character in this story, though I feel as if we still didn't know too much about his true intentions by the end, which makes me think that his intentions were unknown even to him. As the play progresses, our understanding of what relationship remains between him and his wife gets clearer. I really would have loved to know how Henry really felt towards Eleanor during their elder years, but of course we'll never know. That being said, as Henry drops his guard, we see that there is still something between them. I feel like Goldman's Henry was the most believable in terms of what we know about the real Henry and I'm truly impressed with the depiction of him in such a short play. <br /><br /><i>"That's my one advantage over you. You're wiser, shrewder, more experienced. I'm colder; I feel less."</i> - Richard <br /><br /><b>Richard:</b> Ah Richard. Goldman's Richard is far from a soliloquist, but he definitely has the best one-liners in this play. So much so that I think the author could have removed all of his character tags from the script and I still would have known when it was him talking. It kind of threw me off that Richard was actually fighting <i>to</i> marry Alais since I'm pretty sure he was actually fighting with all of his being <i>not</i> to have to wed her, but I digress. The only aspect of his character that sort of surprised me is when he was extremely heartless and careless… until he wasn't. I really wasn't expecting him to get that emotionally wounded by Philip but I don't think it took anything away from his character. I think Goldman could have done something with that expression but it wasn't really touched upon after that. Maybe if it was a longer play.    <br /><br /><i>"If you're so clever than why am I always doing something stupid?"</i> - John<br /><br /><b>John:</b> Goldman's John is a child, and I love him that way. As hard as it is to admit, I've always liked over-the-top depictions of John. The brattier the better. To my delight, Goldman's John was an absolute asshat. Throughout the play, John battles with both his father and Richard, using Geoffrey as his henchman in the progress. Whereas Richard has a very hot and cold relationship with Eleanor, John's is just plain cold. John's a really enjoyable character to hate and I love the archetype of a character that feigns bravado yet can't seem to make a decision without being spurred on by another (see above quotation). <br /><br /><i>"I don't have to fight to win. Take all you want -- this country, that one. You won't keep it long."</i> - Philip<br /><br /><b>Philip:</b> OK, so. Philip is a very interesting historical character because he tends to be portrayed one of two ways; these two ways being <i>completely opposite</i> of each other. One common persona that is used for Philip is the pious and inexperienced child who will never be able to stand shoulder-to-shoulder with Henry. Goldman did not choose to use this Philip. At first I thought Goldman was going to be very illusive with this Philip's relationship with the sons, but he really doesn't leave us guessing for long. We really aren't sure in the end if Philip was lying about whether he callously used Richard or not. All we know is that, despite his young age, he seems to have Henry's entire brood in the palm of his hand. It's not exactly my preference, but I have no problem with this Philip, and I think Goldman did well with the decision he made to use him.<br /><br />That's it for now. This play was quite literally one of my most enjoyable reads ever, bias intended. I would literally fall out my chair if I had any opportunity to see this played out in the future. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4383025192883505534" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

