  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1204792695" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1204792695" />
    <a title="Susana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12047133-susana"><img alt="Susana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346671784p2/12047133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1204792695?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susana" href="/user/show/12047133-susana">Susana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140481747" href="/book/show/762414.The_Lion_in_Winter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12047133-susana?shelf=theatre">theatre</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12047133-susana?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1204792695" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1125095348853992203">The love of power, the power of love and the power of power. Lovely. Those are the three things the play is about according to Michael Mayer, one of its directors.<br/><br/>I&apos;ve just watched two plays that have absolutely nothing to do with one another despite being pretty much about the same thing: a dysfunctional family get-together for a special occasion (Christmas in one, the grandfather&apos;s suicide in the other). The one is the Lion in Winter, the other August: Osage county.<br/><br/>It&apos;s Christmas 1183. Henry I</span>
  <span id="freeText1125095348853992203" style="display:none">The love of power, the power of love and the power of power. Lovely. Those are the three things the play is about according to Michael Mayer, one of its directors.<br><br>I've just watched two plays that have absolutely nothing to do with one another despite being pretty much about the same thing: a dysfunctional family get-together for a special occasion (Christmas in one, the grandfather's suicide in the other). The one is the Lion in Winter, the other August: Osage county.<br><br>It's Christmas 1183. Henry II has assembled his three ungrateful sons, Richard, Geoffrey and John, his estranged wife, Eleanor of Aquitaine, and Alais, his ward, lover and the fiancée of whichever might be his heir. Her brother Phillip tags along, as he's the king of France and Henry's suzerain. During the holidays, Henry aims to name a successor. I love history, things are always so messed up. <br><br>Alais was raised by the then loving couple and looks up to Eleanor as a mother. Eleanor is Phillip's father ex-wife.<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1424340885ra/13749193.gif" width="150" height="150" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br> <img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1424340885ra/13749194.gif" width="150" height="150" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Facts are stranger than fiction, guys.<br><br>However, the play is only apparently historical. Facts are but the byproduct of the relationships. And what a relationship is Eleanor and Henry's! A classical love/hate that translates into an epic and constant power struggle. He's "a marvel of a man" and she's every bit his match.<br><br>The earliest example of power struggle I remember is in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10791718.Rocambole__Colecci_n_Completa_" title="Rocambole (Colección Completa) by Pierre Alexis Ponson du Terrail" rel="nofollow noopener">Rocambole</a> in which a fallen woman and a criminal mastermind try to convince each other that they've nothing but trust and love for one another. She would love nothing more than shoot him in the face. He'd delight in seing her suffer and then die. At stake, their lives plus that of her loved ones.<br><br>And that defines a power struggle. Two characters walk into a room. Each wants something from the other. The question is, who gets what they want? <br><br>One of the best is Clarice Starling and Hannibal Lecter's first meeting. For a far better analysis than I could do, watch this video: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5V-k-p4wzxg" rel="nofollow noopener">The Silence of the Lambs - Who Wins the Scene?</a><br><br>Tarantino also loves this kind of scene. Some of his movies are nothing but a string of power struggles with violent releases. Inglorious Basterds comes to mind. His shifting power dynamics are somewhat less effective because there's simply too many of them. For it to be a really good one the characters involved must love the game and respect each other's abilities. Therein lies Hans Landa's scenes' success.<br><br>Henry and Eleanor are able to sustain this dynamic during the whole play. He left her for softer women who don't scheme and plot his death with every breath. Can you believe it? <br>She looks at him and sees "cities, acreage, coastline, taxes" too. He looks at her and sees the Aquitaine too. They flirt and hurt each other and never let go of their goals.<br><i><br>Henry II: Time hasn't done a thing but wrinkle you.<br>Eleanor: It hasn't even done that. I've borne six girls, five boys... and thirty-one connubial years of you. How am I possible?<br>Henry II: There are moments when I miss you.<br>Eleanor: Many?<br>Henry II: Do you doubt it? </i><br><br><i> Henry II: Don't fight me, Eleanor.<br>Eleanor: What would you have me do? Give out, give up, give in?<br>Henry II: Give me a little peace.<br>Eleanor: A little? Why so modest? How about eternal peace? Now, there's a thought. <br></i> <br>Their sons just can't live up to them. Richard depends on his mother to get the kingdom for him. To do this he employs the curious strategy of telling her he neither loves her nor trusts her. John relies on his father to do so but betrays him at the first chance he gets. Geoffrey promises and lies and nobody but John ever believes him.<br><br>Why isn't he ever considered to be king, he and I both wonder? There's really not much of a difference between his behaviour and his mother's. They both negotiate with nothing (the Aquitaine is Richard's). But Eleanor is going to win, as anybody familiar with Robin Hood knows. While it's dubious she truly loves Richard, she's humanized by her sincere love of Henry and Alais whereas Geoffrey is "a device. He's wheels and gears".<br><br>Eleanor is priceless. A powerful duchess of her own right, two times queen and once regent. She's thought to have been extroverted, intelligent, strong willed and cultivated. One of the biggest patrons of the arts of her age, she headed a Cour d'Amour in Poitiers with her daughter Marie de Champagne.<br><br>In the movie she's played by Katharine Hepburn. The cast is all-around awesome but she's in a league of her own. Which other actress, ever, could play such a smart, independent, fierce, dry, funny woman? My second choices would be Maggie Smith (because she's Maggie Smith) or Emma Thompson (because of Much Ado about Nothing). Maybe Meryl Streep (because she can do anything).<br><br>If we add a truly masterful use of tapestries we get one of the best plays I've ever have the pleasure of reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1125095348853992203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

